revision.text:
The '''C-2 visa''' is a non-immigrant [[Visa (document)|visa]] which allows individuals to travel to [[United States]] for the purpose of immediate and continuous transit to or from the [[headquarters of the United Nations]], or for United Nations officials transiting the US to another foreign nation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Transit Visa|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/visas/en/other/transit.html|website=US Department of State Bureau of Consular Affairs|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref> The holders of such a visa are considered "geographically restricted nonimmigrants".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uscis.gov/ilink/docView/AFM/HTML/AFM/0-0-0-1/0-0-0-12693/0-0-0-13504.html|title=30.9 Geographically Restricted Nonimmigrants. {{!}} USCIS|website=www.uscis.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-10-11}}</ref>
==United Nations Headquarters District== The travel area for recipients of a C-2 visa is limited to a 25-mile radius of [[Columbus Circle]], which is [[New York City]]'s equivalent of the [[Kilometre zero|zero mile marker]] — the area of this circle is known in the [[Title 22 of the United States Code|U.S. Code, Title 22]] as the "United Nations Headquarters District".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/22/4309a|title=22 U.S. Code § 4309a - United States responsibilities for employees of the United Nations|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|language=en|access-date=2017-10-10}}</ref> The visa is valid for the duration of the individual's stay at the United Nations.<ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date=2013 |title=Immigration pocket field guide|url= |location= |publisher=Matthew Bender & Company, Inc|page=29 |isbn=}}</ref> This is most relevant for countries that do not have good relations with the United States. The office of the [[Permanent Representative of Iran to the United Nations]] commissioned an informal survey with [[Hagstrom Map]] determining that the covered area had boundaries at [[Parsippany-Troy Hills, New Jersey|Parsippany, New Jersey]], the [[Connecticut]] border, and Exit 40 of the [[Interstate 495 (New York)|Long Island Expressway]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/26/world/asia/26zarif.html|title=Within 25 Miles of New York, Iran Offers a Congenial Glow|last=Hoge|first=Warren|date=2007-05-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-10-09|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>
