The '''Electronic System for Travel Authorization''' ('''ESTA''') is an automated system that determines the eligibility of visitors to travel to the [[United States]] under the [[Visa Waiver Program]] (VWP).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://esta.cbp.dhs.gov/esta/application.html?execution=e1s1|title=Home - Official ESTA Application Website, U.S. Customs and Border Protection|website=esta.cbp.dhs.gov}}</ref> ESTA was mandated by the [[Implementing Recommendations of the 9/11 Commission Act of 2007]] for travelers from VWP countries arriving in the U.S. by air or sea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/110/plaws/publ53/PLAW-110publ53.pdf|title=IMPLEMENTING RECOMMENDATIONS OF THE 9/11 COMMISSION ACT OF 2007|publisher=}}</ref> Authorization via ESTA does not determine whether a traveler is admissible to the United States. [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection]] (CBP) officers determine admissibility upon travelers’ arrival. The ESTA application collects biographic information and answers to VWP eligibility questions. ESTA applications may be submitted at any time prior to travel, though it is recommended that travelers apply as soon as they begin preparing travel plans or prior to purchasing airline tickets.

ESTA is not needed when arriving by land from Canada or Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.cbp.gov/app/answers/detail/a_id/1094/kw/esta/related/1|title=Who must apply for ESTA|work=US Customs and Border Protection|accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref> Passengers (including babies) without an ESTA may be denied check in, although it might be possible to get one while at the departure airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://esta.cbp.dhs.gov/esta/WebHelp/ESTA_Screen-Level_Online_Help_1.htm#TA7|title=Electronic System for Travel Authorization (ESTA) Online Help|work=US Customs and Border Protection|accessdate=November 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>Check-in staff is unlikely to do this. It might be done by a travel agent or by oneself using a smartphone or an internet café.</ref> In 2010, U.S. Customs and Border Protection began charging a fee of US $14 per ESTA application.

== History ==
Passengers were able to sign up in August 2008, and the travel authorization became mandatory from January 12, 2009. Once pre-screened, passengers may reuse the ESTA approval for two years, although they may still need to complete the I-94W paper form for land entry.<ref name=I94W>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbp.gov/travel/international-visitors/i-94-instructions |title=Arrival/Departure Forms: I-94 and I-94W |date=July 19, 2010 |accessdate=November 12, 2016}}</ref>

ESTA adds a requirement for pre-authorization to the existing Visa Waiver Program.

Since January 20, 2010, airlines have been forced (through fines) to require ESTA at check in.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etravelblackboard.com/showarticle.asp?id=101402&nav=13 |title=Electronic System for Travel Authorization Compliance Now Required &#124;ETB News Australia |publisher=Etravelblackboard.com |date= |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>

Before September 8, 2010, ESTA was available for free from the official government websites. Since then, the [[Travel Promotion Act of 2009|Travel Promotion Act]] introduced a charge of $14. This is made up of $10 which goes to the Corporation for Travel Promotion and a $4 fee levied by the CBP for administration costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbp.gov/xp/cgov/newsroom/news_releases/national/08062010_2.xml |title=DHS, CBP Announce Interim Final Rule For ESTA Fee |date=August 6, 2010 |work=CPB.gov |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015092651/http://cbp.gov/xp/cgov/newsroom/news_releases/national/08062010_2.xml |archivedate=October 15, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> The EU Ambassador to the United States [[John Bruton]] argued that it is illogical to think tourist numbers will go up if they are charged to enter the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurunion.org/eu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3466&Itemid=58 |title=Travel Promotion Act of 2009 could have unintended consequences |date=September 4, 2009 |accessdate=November 12, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100625221119/http://www.eurunion.org/eu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=3466&Itemid=58 |archivedate=June 25, 2010 |df=mdy }}</ref>
The charge has also been described by critics in the European Parliament as little more than a way to fund advertisements for United States tourism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visabureau.com/america/news/27-09-2010/european-parliament-criticizes-esta-fee-to-fund-travel-promotion.aspx |title=European Parliament criticizes ESTA fee to fund travel promotion |publisher=Visabureau.com |date=2010-09-27 |accessdate=2014-05-20}}</ref>

