{{Politics of Samoa}}
A '''double referendum''' on a [[Constitution of Samoa|new constitution]] and [[independence referendum|independence]] took place in [[Western Samoa]] on 10 May 1961. A Constitutional Convention of [[Fa'amatai|Matai]] and associated groups had drawn up a proposed constitution. It reflected the [[Westminster system]] of parliamentary democracy, but restricted both standing and voting in elections to the Matai.<ref>Nohlen, D, Grotz, F & Hartmann, C (2001) ''Elections in Asia: A data handbook, Volume II'', p780 {{ISBN|0-19-924959-8}}</ref> The referendums were supervised by the [[United Nations]], and with both approved, the country gained independence on 1 January the following year.
==Results== ===Independence=== {{blockquote|Do you agree that on 1 January 1962 Western Samoa should become an independent State on the basis of that Constitution?<ref>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=ws021961 West-Samoa, 10. Mai 1961 : Unabhängigkeit] Direct Democracy</ref>}} {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Choice !Votes !% |- |align=left|For||29,882||85.40 |- |align=left|Against||5,108||14.60 |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||2,907||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''37,897'''||'''100''' |- |align=left colspan=3|Source: [http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=ws021961 Direct Democracy] |}
===New constitution=== {{blockquote|Do you agree with the Constitution, adopted by the Constitutional Convention on 28 October 1960?<ref>[http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=ws011961 West-Samoa, 10. Mai 1961 : Verfassung] Direct Democracy</ref>}} {| class=wikitable style=text-align:right !Choice !Votes !% |- |align=left|For||31,426||86.49 |- |align=left|Against||4,909||13.51 |- |align=left|Invalid/blank votes||1,562||– |- |align=left|'''Total'''||'''37,897'''||'''100''' |- |align=left colspan=3|Source: [http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=ws011961 Direct Democracy] |}
